Here is the contract code based on your descriptions:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.5.5;

contract YourContract {
    address payable recipient1 = 0xF4c6BB681800Ffb96Bc046F56af9f06Ab5774156;
    address payable recipient2 = 0xD79D762727A6eeb9c47Cfb6FB451C858dfBF8405;
    address payable recipient3 = 0x83c0Efc6d8B16D87BFe1335AB6BcAb3Ed3960285;

    function get() public payable {
        uint256 balance = address(this).balance;
        uint256 amount = balance / 3;

        (bool success1,) = recipient1.call.value(amount)("");
        require(success1, "Transfer failed.");

        (bool success2,) = recipient2.call.value(amount)("");
        require(success2, "Transfer failed.");

        balance = address(this).balance;
        (bool success3,) = recipient3.call.value(balance)("");
        require(success3, "Transfer failed.");
    }

    function() external payable {}
}
```

In this contract, the `get` function divides the contract's balance into three parts. It then sends one part to `recipient1`, another part to `recipient2`, and the remaining balance to `recipient3`. 

The code uses `call.value` to send ether to the specified addresses. The `require` function is used after each transfer to ensure that the transfer was successful. If the transfer fails, the whole transaction will be reverted.

The fallback function is used to receive ethers sent to the contract.
